  "title": "Section 1.2 - Reduced row echelon form (Part 2)",
  "body": " Section 1.2 - Reduced row echelon form (Part 2)    Make sure you can answer the following questions:    When is a matrix in reduced row echelon form?  Describe how to put a matrix in reduced row echelon from.  How do we use the reduced row echelon form to determine the solution space?      Consider each of the following augmented matrices. In the class prep you determined if these were in reduced row echelon form. If a matrix is not in reduced row echelon form, either (a) perform a sequence of scaling, interchange, and replacement operations to obtain a row equivalent matrix that is in reduced row echelon form or (b) use Sage to find the row reduced echelon form. Then use the reduced row echelon matrix to determine whether there is a single solution, infinitely many solutions, or no solutions. If there are infinitely many, identify free and basic variables.           Suppose that the reduced row echelon form of a matrix looks like What, if anything, does the last row tell you about the solution space?  Suppose that the reduced row echelon form of a matrix looks like What, if anything, does the last row tell you about the solution space?  If a linear system has no solutions, how can you tell by looking at the reduced row echelon form of its augmented matrix.      Consider the system of linear equations:   Form the associated augmented matrix and perform Gaussian elimination (or use Sage) to find its reduced row echelon form. What does this tell you about the solution space of the system?    "
